Black miners, rebelling against theloneliness of men-only hostels, have brought wives and childrento live with them at seven South African coal mines, a unionleader said today.    Cyril Ramaphosa told a news conference about 600 wives andchildren moved into the hostels last weekend, in defiance ofsingle-sex regulations. About 350 left after the weekend butthe others stayed on.    "The time has come for them (miners and families) to startliving naturally," said Ramaphosa, who is president of theNational Union of Mineworkers (NUM).    A spokesman for Anglo-American, the giant corporation whichowns the mines affected, said negotiations were being held withthe NUM on the issue. Reuter&#3;